{
  "title": "Designing Cron-Driven Tasks with FastAPI in Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This guide explains how to set up and manage scheduled tasks using FastAPI, a modern web framework for building APIs, along with the cron scheduler in Python 3.12+.",
  "key_points": [
    "Create an asynchronous FastAPI application",
    "Use AIOHTTP or other third-party libraries to handle HTTP requests",
    "Write the task function for your scheduled job",
    "Set up a cron job to trigger the FastAPI endpoint at desired intervals",
    "Handle errors and retries effectively"
  ],
  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "```\nimport fastapi\nimport aiohttp\n\napp = fastapi.FastAPI()\n\ngreet = app.get('/')\nasync def greet_handler():\n    return {'hello': 'world'} \n\n@greet.on_event('task_every_minutes')\nasync def task():\n    # Your scheduled task code here\n```"
    },
    {
      "language": "bash",
      "code": "\n# In crontab:\n0 * * * * cd /path/to/project && python -m fastapi task > /dev/null 2>&1"
    }
  ],
  "version_notes": [
    "Python 3.12+ is required for the AIOHTTP library",
    "FastAPI versions v0.70 and later support FastAPI events, which enable cron-driven tasks"
  ],
  "caveats": [
    "Ensure that your scheduled task does not block other operations or exceed resource limits",
    "Consider using third-party libraries like Celery for more complex and scalable job scheduling solutions"
  ]
}
